trans-unit.source:
In Haskell 98, the inferred kind for <code>App</code> is <code>(Type -&gt; Type) -&gt; Type -&gt;
Type</code>. But this is overly specific, because another suitable Haskell 98 kind for <code>App</code> is <code>((Type -&gt; Type) -&gt; Type) -&gt; (Type -&gt; Type) -&gt; Type</code>, where the kind assigned to <code>a</code> is <code>Type -&gt; Type</code>. Indeed, without kind signatures (<a href="#extension-KindSignatures"><code>KindSignatures</code></a>), it is necessary to use a dummy constructor to get a Haskell compiler to infer the second kind. With kind polymorphism (<a href="#extension-PolyKinds"><code>PolyKinds</code></a>), GHC infers the kind <code>forall k. (k -&gt; Type) -&gt; k -&gt;
Type</code> for <code>App</code>, which is its most general kind.
